ce:section.ce:para:
To study the kinetics of the sensing platform, the temporal fluorescence profile of the HQCA solution was recorded over the addition of Th4+/Fe3+. As shown in Fig. 3b, the addition of Th4+/Fe3+ to HQCA (2 × 10−5 M) displayed a rapid increment in the fluorescence intensity and reached the plateau in 2 s. This is due to the immediate formation of the complex between HQCA and Th4+/Fe3+. Therefore, no cultivation time was needed to record fluorescence spectra, which indicated that HQCA has a potential application with the real-time detection of Th4+ and Fe3+. Furthermore, the quantitative sensing behaviour of HQCA towards Th4+ and Fe3+ was studied by fluorescence titration in acetonitrile/water (8:2) mixture solvent. As shown in Fig. 4
                        a and Fig. 4c, the incremental addition of Th4+ or Fe3+ induced gradual enhancement in the fluorescence intensity of HQCA. The plot of fluorescence intensity ratio against the increasing concentration of Th4+ or Fe3+ showed excellent linearity with their respective R2, which was found to be 0.9993 and 0.9985 (Fig. 4b and d). The binding constant (
                           K
                        ) for [HQCA + Th

                           4+
                        ] and HQCA + Fe

                           3+
                        ] was 5.67 × 103 M−1and 8.78 × 103 M−1. High sensitivity is an important attribute of a sensor. Limit of detection (LOD) of HQCA “turn on” towards Th4+ and Fe3+ was determined following the 3σ/K method.
